JOHANNESBURG - Gun Owners South Africa wants Police Minister Bheki Cele to terminate the firearm amnesty and start a new process, approved by Parliament. The association says the amnesty was rushed. READ: Is owning a gun a right or a privilege? It started on 1 December and will apply until the end of May 2020. Paul Oxley, chairperson of Gun Owners South Africa, said the organisation is not against an amnesty programme in theory, but said the amnesty is designed to confiscate guns from owners whose licenses have expired. READ: More women arming themselves Oxley maintains the reason behind many of the expirations is due to police administrative problems. He said the conditions of the amnesty bill are not legal and claimed members of Parliament were intimidated into pushing the legislation through.